ss | first7 = P. K. | last8 = Matthews | first8 = M. L. | last9 = Stevens | first9 = P. F. | last10 = Mathews | first10 = S. | last11 = Davis | first11 = C. C. | doi = 10.1073/pnas.1205818109 | title = Phylogenomics and ''a posteriori'' data partitioning resolve the Cretaceous angiosperm radiation Malpighiales | journal = [[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences]] | volume = 109 | issue = 43 | pages = 17519 | year = 2012 | pmid =  23045684| pmc = 3491498|ref={{harvid|Xi et al|2012}}}}\n\n;Websites\n* {{cite web |last=WFO|authorlink=World Flora Online|title=Violaceae Batsch |url=http://www.worldfloraonline.org/taxon/wfo-7000000637 |website=World Flora Online |accessdate=27 February 2020 |date=2019|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web |last=IPNI|authorlink=International Plant Names Index|title=Violaceae Batsch, Tab. Affin. Regni Veg. 57 (1802)  |url=https://www.ipni.org/n/30000541-2|publisher=[[Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew]]|accessdate=23 March 2020|ref={{harvid|IPNI|2020}} }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commonscat}}{{wikispecies}}\n\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q156060}}\n\n[[Category:Malpighiales families]]\n[[Category:Violaceae| ]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by August Batsch]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|A family of flowering plants in the eudicot order Malpighiales, including violets and pansies}}\n{{Automatic taxobox\n|image = Viola hedercea01.jpg\n|image_caption = ''[[Viola banksii]]''\n|taxon = Violaceae\n|authority = [[August Batsch|Batsch]]\n|subdivision = [[#Subdivision|Subfamilies]]\n}}\n\n'''Violaceae''' is a [[family (biology)|family]] of [[flowering plant]]s consisting of about 1000 species in about 25 genera. It takes its name from the [[genus]] ''[[Viola (plant)|Viola]]'',  the violets and [[pansy|pansies]].\n\nOlder classifications such as the [[Cronquist system]] placed the Violaceae in an [[order (biology)|order]] named after it, the [[Violales]]. However, more recent classifications such as that of the [[Angiosperm Phylogeny Group]] locate it in the [[Malpighiales]].\n\n==Description==\n\nThough the best-known genus, ''Viola'', is [[herbaceous]], most species are [[shrubs]], [[lianas]] or small [[trees]].{{sfn|Wahlert et al|2014}}  The simple [[leaves]] are alternate or opposite, often with leafy stipules or the stipules are reduced in size. Some species have palmate or deeply dissected leaves. Many species are acaulescent. Inflorescences have solitary flowers or are paniculate; some species have cleistogamous flowers produced after or before the production of typically petaled flowers. Flowers are bisexual or unisexual (e.g. ''Melicytus''), typically zygomorphic or actinomorphic with a calyx of five sepals that are persistent after flowering. Corollae have five mostly unequal petals, and the anterior petal is larger and often spurred. Plants have five stamens with the abaxial stamen often spurred at the base. The gynoecium is a compound pistil of three united carpels with one [[locule]].  Styles are simple, with the ovary superior, and many ovules. The fruits are capsules split by way of three seams.  Seeds have endosperm.\n\n== Taxonomy ==\n\nViolaceae, as a suprageneric rank, was described by [[Batsch]] (1802), under the name of Violariae, and bears his name as the [[botanical authority]].{{sfn|Batsch|1802}} Batsch included eight [[genera]] in this [[Family (biology)|family]].{{sfn|IPNI|2020}} Although Violariae continued to be used by some authors, such as [[Bentham and Hooker]] in 1862 (as Violarieae),{{sfn|Bentham|Hooker|1862}} most authors adopted the alternative name Violaceae, proposed by by [[de Lamarck]] and [[de Candolle]] in 1805,{{sfn|de Lamarck|de Candolle|1815}} and later by [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Charles Jean Gingins de la Sarraz|Gingins]] in 1823.{{sfn|Gingins|1823}} With the establishment of higher suprafamiliar orders, which he called \"Alliances\", [[John Lindley|Lindley]] (1853) placed his Violaceae within the Violales.{{sfn|Lindley|1853}}\n\nViolaceae is one of a large number of [[Families (biology)|families]] within the modern [[eudicot]] [[Order (biology)|order]] [[Malpighiales]]. They are a medium sized family with about 22\u201328 [[genera]], and about 1,000\u20131,100 [[species]]. Most of the genera are [[monotypic]] or [[oligotypic]], but the three genera ''[[Viola (plant)|Viola]]'' (about 600 species), ''[[Rinorea]]'' (about 250 species), and ''[[Hybanthus]]'' include 98% of the species.{{sfn|Wahlert et al|2014}}{{sfn|WFO|2019}}{{sfn|APG IV|2016}} \n\n=== Phylogeny ===\n\nViolaceae, as one of 42 families, is placed in a [[clade]] of 10 families within the order.{{sfn|Xi et al|2012}}{{sfn|Wahlert et al|2014}}\n\n{{Clade| style=line-height:75%;\n|1={{clade\n  |1=[[Oxalidales]]&nbsp;([[Outgroup (cladistics)|outgroup]])\n  |label2=[[Malpighiales]]{{sfn|Xi et al|2012}}\n  |2={{clade\n    |1={{clade\n      |label1=euphorbioids\n      |1={{clade\n        |1={{clade\n          |1=[[Euphorbiaceae]]\n          |2=[[Peraceae]]\n           }}\n        |2={{clade\n          |label1=phyllanthoids\n          |1={{clade\n            |1=[[Picrodendraceae]]\n            |2=[[Phyllanthaceae]]\n             }}\n          |label2=linoids\n          |2={{clade\n            |1=[[Linaceae]]\n            |2=[[Ixonanthaceae]]\n             }}\n           }}\n         }}\n      |2={{clade\n        |label1=parietal&nbsp;clade\n        |1={{clade\n          |1={{clade\n            |label1=salicoids\n            |1={{clade\n              |1={{clade\n                |1={{clade\n                  |1={{clade\n                    |1=[[Salicaceae]]\n                    |2=[[Scyphostegiaceae]]\n                     }}\n                  |2=[[Samydaceae]]\n                   }}\n                |2=[[Lacistemataceae]]\n                 }}\n              |2={{clade\n                |1={{clade\n                  |1=[[Passifloraceae]]\n                  |2=[[Turneraceae]]\n                   }}\n                |2=[[Malesherbiaceae]]\n                 }}\n               }}\n            |2={{clade\n              |1='''Violaceae'''\n              |2=[[Goupiaceae]]\n               }}\n             }}\n          |2=[[Achariaceae]]\n           }}\n        |2=[[Humiriaceae]]\n         }}\n       }}\n    |2={{clade\n      |1={{clade\n        |label1=clusioids\n        |1={{clade\n          |1={{clade\n            |1={{clade\n              |1=[[Hypericaceae]]\n              |2=[[Podostemaceae]]\n               }}\n            |2=[[Calophyllaceae]]\n             }}\n          |2={{clade\n            |1=[[Clusiaceae]]\n            |2=[[Bonnetiaceae]]\n             }}\n           }}\n        |label2=ochnoids\n        |2={{clade\n          |1=[[Ochnaceae]]\n          |2={{clade\n            |1=[[Quiinaceae]]\n            |2=[[Medusagynaceae]]\n             }}\n           }}\n         }}\n      |2={{clade\n        |1={{clade\n          |1=[[Rhizophoraceae]]\n          |2=[[Erythroxylaceae]]\n           }}\n        |2=[[Ctenolophonaceae]]\n         }}\n      |3={{clade\n        |1=[[Pandaceae]]\n        |2=[[Irvingiaceae]]\n         }}\n       }}\n    |3={{clade\n      |label1=chrysobalanoids\n      |1={{clade\n        |1={{clade\n          |1={{clade\n            |1=[[Chrysobalanaceae]]\n            |2=[[Euphroniaceae]]\n             }}\n          |2={{clade\n            |1=[[Dichapetalaceae]]\n            |2=[[Trigoniaceae]]\n             }}\n           }}\n        |2=[[Balanopaceae]]\n         }}\n      |label2=malpighioids\n      |2={{clade\n        |1={{clade\n          |1=[[Malpighiaceae]]\n          |2=[[Elatinaceae]]\n           }}\n        |2=[[Centroplacaceae]]\n         }}\n      |3=[[Caryocaraceae]]\n      |label4=putranjivoids\n      |4={{clade\n        |1=[[Putranjivaceae]]\n        |2=[[Lophopyxidaceae]]\n         }}\n       }}\n     }}\n   }}\n}}\n\n=== Subdivision ===\n\nMany attempts have been made at an intrafamilial classification, but these have largelybeen artificial, based on floral characteristics, but [[molecular phylogenetic]] studies have revealed that many of these divisions were not [[monophyletic]], partly due to [[homoplasy]]. These studies demonstrate four major clades within the family.{{sfn|Wahlert et al|2014}} \n\nThe historical subdivisions shown here are those of the system of Hekking (1988). Three [[subfamily|subfamilies]] are recognized: the [[Violoideae]], [[Leonioideae]], and [[Fusispermoideae]].{{sfn|Hekking|1988}}{{sfn|Wahlert et al|2014}}\n\n==== Subfamily Fusispermoideae ====\n*''[[Fusispermum]]'' <small>[[Cuatrec.]]</small>\n\n==== Subfamily Leonioideae ====\n*''[[Leonia (plant)|Leonia]]'' <small>[[Hip\u00f3lito Ruiz L\u00f3pez|Ruiz]] & [[Pav.]]</small>\n\n==== Subfamily Violoideae ====\n\n===== Tribe Rinoreeae =====\n\n====== Subtribe [[Hymenantherinae]] ======\n*''[[Hymenanthera]]'' <small>[[Robert Brown (Scottish botanist from Montrose)|R.Br.]]</small>\n*''[[Melicytus]]'' <small>[[Johann Reinhold Forster|J.R.Forst.]] & [[Georg Forster|G.Forst.]]</small>\n\n====== Subtribe [[Isodendriinae]] ======\n*''[[Isodendrion]]'' <small>[[Asa Gray|A.Gray]]</small>\n\n====== Subtribe [[Paypayrolinae]] ======\n*''[[Amphirrhox]]'' <small>[[Spreng.]]</small>\n*''[[Paypayrola]]'' <small>[[Jean Baptiste Christophore Fus\u00e9e Aublet|Aubl.]]</small> (including ''Hekkingia'' <small>[[J. K. Munzinger]] & [[H.E.Ballard]]</small>)\n\n====== Subtribe [[Rinoreinae]] ======\n*''[[Allexis]]'' <small>[[Jean Baptiste Louis Pierre|Pierre]]</small>\n*''[[Decorsella]]'' <small>[[A.Chev.]]</small> (including ''Gymnorinorea'' <small>[[Keay]]</small>)\n*''[[Gloeospermum]]'' <small>[[Jos\u00e9 J\u00e9ronimo Triana|Triana]] & [[Planch.]]</small>\n*''[[Rinorea]]'' <small>[[Jean Baptiste Christophore Fus\u00e9e Aublet|Aubl.]]</small> (including ''Alsodeia'' <small>[[Louis-Marie Aubert du Petit-Thouars|Thouars]]</small>, ''Phyllanoa'' <small>[[L\u00e9on Croizat|Croizat]]</small>, ''Scyphellandra'' <small>[[George Henry Kendrick Thwaites|Thwaites]]</small>)\n*''[[Rinoreocarpus]]'' <small>[[Adolpho Ducke|Ducke]]</small>\n\n===== Tribe Violeae =====\n*''[[Anchietea]]'' <small>[[A.St.-Hil.]]</small>\n*''[[Corynostylis]]'' <small>[[Carl Friedrich Philipp von Martius|Mart.]]</small> (including ''Agatea'' <small>[[Asa Gray|A.Gray]]</small> and ''Agation'' <small>[[Brongn.]]</small>)\n*''[[Hybanthopsis]]'' <small>[[Paula-Souza]]</small>\n*''[[Hybanthus]]'' <small>[[Nikolaus Joseph von Jacquin|Jacq.]]</small> (included ''Acentra'' <small>[[Rodolfo Amando Philippi|Phil.]]</small>, ''Clelandia'' <small>[[J.M.Black]]</small>, ''Cubelium'' <small>[[Constantine Samuel Rafinesque-Schmaltz|Raf.]] ex [[Nathaniel Lord Britton|Britton]] & [[A.Br.]]</small>, ''Ionidium'' <small>[[Vent.]]</small>, ''Pigea'' <small>[[A. P. de Candolle|DC.]]</small>)\n*''[[Mayanaea]]'' <small>[[Cyrus Longworth Lundell|Lundell]]</small>\n*''[[Noisettia]]'' <small>[[Carl Sigismund Kunth|Kunth]]</small>\n*''[[Orthion]]'' <small>[[Standl.]] & [[Steyerm.]]</small>\n*''[[Schweiggeria]]'' <small>[[Spreng.]]</small>\n*''[[Viola (plant)|Viola]]'' <small>[[Carl Linnaeus|L.]]</small> (including ''Erpetion'' <small>[[Robert Sweet (botanist)|Sweet]]</small>, ''Mnemion'' <small>[[\u00c9douard Spach|Spach]]</small>)\n\n==== Clades ====\n\nThe molecularly defined subdivisions are;{{sfn|Wahlert et al|2014}}\n* Clade 1: ''Viola'', ''[[Schweiggeria]]'', ''[[Noisettia]]'', ''[[Allexis]]''\n* Clade 2: ''[[Paypayrola]]'', ''[[Hekkingia]]''\n* Clade 3: ''[[Leonia]]'', ''[[Gloeospermum]]'', ''[[Amphirrhox]]'', ''[[Orthion]]'', ''[[Mayanaea]]'', ''[[Hybanthus concolor]]'', the ''[[Hybanthus havanensis]]'' Group, and the ''[[Hybanthus caledonicus]]'' Group\n* Clade 4: largely uresolved\n\nIn Clade 1, ''Schweiggeria'' and ''Noisettia'' are monotypic and form a sister group to ''Viola''. In addition to the major clades, there were a number of unplaced segregates.{{sfn|Wahlert et al|2014}}\n\n== Distribution and habitat ==\n\nThe Violaceae have a [[cosmopolitan distribution]].{{sfn|Wahlert et al|2014}} \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n;Books\n* {{cite book|last1=Ballard|first1=Harvey E|last2=Paula-Souza|first2=Juliana de|last3=Wahlert|first3=Gregory A|editor-last=Kubitzki|editor-first=Klaus|editorlink=Klaus Kubitzki|title=Flowering Plants. 11 Eudicots: Malpighiales|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4vlkyAEACAAJ|date=2013|publisher=[[Springer Science & Business Media]]|isbn=978-3-642-39417-1|chapter=Violaceae|pages=303\u2013322|chapter-url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/270759276|ref=harv}}{{link note|note=Also preview at [https://www.springer.com/life+sciences/plant+sciences/book/978-3-642-39416-4 Springer]}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Batsch|first1=August Johann Georg Karl|authorlink=August Batsch|title=Tabula affinitatum regni vegetabilis, quam delineavit, et nunc ulterius adumbratam |date=1802|publisher=Landes-Industrie-Comptoir|location=[[Weimar]]|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/bibliography/7569#/summary|language=la|chapter=Violariae|pages=57\u201359|chapter-url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/31965#page/77/mode/1up|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Bentham|first1=G.|last2=Hooker|first2=J.D.|authorlink1=George Bentham|authorlink2=JD Hooker| title=Genera plantarum ad exemplaria imprimis in herbariis kewensibus servata definita|format=3 vols.|year=1862|publisher=L Reeve & Co.|location=London|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/bibliography/747#/summary|volume=1(1)|chapter=Violarieae|pages=114\u2013121|chapter-url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/14680#page/125/mode/1up|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Byng|first1=James W.|authorlink=James W. Byng|title=The Flowering Plants Handbook: A practical guide to families and genera of the world|date=2014|publisher=Plant Gateway Ltd.|isbn=978-0-9929993-1-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yoLaBAAAQBAJ|chapter=Violaceae|pages=238\u2013239|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Christenhusz|first1=Maarten J. M.|last2=Fay|first2=Michael F.|last3=Chase|first3=Mark W.|authorlink1=M